            "title": "Phospholipid Bilayer Structure",
            "subtitle": "Why cells need a membrane — and how phospholipids build one automatically",
            "video": {
                "id": "qBCVVszQQNs",
                "title": "Inside the Cell Membrane",
                "channel": "Amoeba Sisters",
                "time": "9:09"
            },
            "reading": "<p>Imagine you soak a raw egg in vinegar for 24 hours. The vinegar dissolves the hard shell, but the egg doesn't fall apart. Underneath the shell, there is a thin, flexible layer that holds everything together. This layer is similar to a <dfn data-def=\"The flexible outer boundary of a cell — controls what enters and leaves\" tabindex=\"0\">cell membrane</dfn> — a barrier that is flexible, not rigid, but still strong enough to keep the inside of the cell separate from the outside.</p>\n\n<p>Every cell needs this barrier because of <strong class=\"ck-hl\">homeostasis</strong> — the process of maintaining a stable internal environment. The cell must keep the right materials inside (like water, proteins, and DNA) and keep harmful materials out. At the same time, the cell must let useful things in (like nutrients) and let waste products out.</p>\n\n<p>The cell membrane does this by being <dfn data-def=\"Allows some materials through but not others — 'semi' means partial\" tabindex=\"0\">semi-permeable</dfn>. \"Semi\" means partial. A semi-permeable membrane lets some materials through but not others. Small, nonpolar molecules like oxygen and carbon dioxide can pass through easily. But large or charged molecules — like glucose or sodium ions — cannot pass through on their own. They need help from special proteins in the membrane.</p>\n\n<p>Before we look at the membrane's structure, you need two vocabulary words. Both come from Greek roots:</p>\n\n<p><strong class=\"ck-hl\">💧 Hydrophilic = \"water-loving.\"</strong> <em>Hydro</em> = water. <em>Philic</em> = loving. <dfn data-def=\"Water-loving — dissolves in or is attracted to water (polar or charged molecules)\" tabindex=\"0\">Hydrophilic</dfn> substances dissolve in water. They are polar or charged, so water molecules are attracted to them. Examples: salts, sugars, ions.</p>\n\n<p><strong class=\"ck-hl\">🛢️ Hydrophobic = \"water-fearing.\"</strong> <em>Hydro</em> = water. <em>Phobic</em> = fearing. <dfn data-def=\"Water-fearing — does NOT dissolve in water (nonpolar molecules like oils and fats)\" tabindex=\"0\">Hydrophobic</dfn> substances do NOT dissolve in water. They are nonpolar, so water molecules push them away. Examples: oils, fats, waxes.</p>\n\n<p>Now you are ready for the key molecule. A <dfn data-def=\"A lipid with a hydrophilic phosphate head and two hydrophobic fatty acid tails — the main building block of cell membranes\" tabindex=\"0\">phospholipid</dfn> is a special type of lipid (fat) that has two very different parts: a <strong>head</strong> containing a phosphate group (polar → hydrophilic → loves water) and <strong>two tails</strong> made of fatty acid chains (nonpolar → hydrophobic → fears water).</p>\n\n<p>A molecule that has both a hydrophilic part AND a hydrophobic part is called <dfn data-def=\"Having both a water-loving part and a water-fearing part in the same molecule\" tabindex=\"0\">amphipathic</dfn>. This dual nature is the key to everything. It explains why the membrane builds itself.</p>\n\n<p>Here is the beautiful part: <strong>you don't need instructions to build a cell membrane.</strong> If you put phospholipids in water, they arrange themselves automatically. Why? Because the heads love water and the tails hate water. The tails are pushed away from the water molecules — scientists call this the <strong>hydrophobic effect</strong>. The only way to hide all the tails from water is to form two layers, with the tails pointing inward toward each other and the heads pointing outward toward the water on both sides.</p>\n\n<p>This is the <dfn data-def=\"Two layers of phospholipids arranged tail-to-tail — the basic structure of all cell membranes\" tabindex=\"0\">phospholipid bilayer</dfn>. \"Bi\" means two. Two layers of phospholipids, arranged tail-to-tail. The bilayer curves around to form a complete sphere surrounding the entire cell. Inside the sphere: the cell's cytoplasm (water-based). Outside: the extracellular fluid (also water-based). The hydrophilic heads face both sides. The hydrophobic tails are safely hidden in the middle, never touching water.</p>",
